passages.text: 2Q25: Strong PPOP and profits growth, while NIM pressure lingers

2Q results: Incremental messages are mixed. BoHZ had pre- announced strong 2Q profits growth of \(+16\%\) y/y in Jul- 25 (link); we believe the full report delivered mixed messages. On the positive side: 1) 2Q PPOP \((+7\% y / y)\) beat JPME by \(13\%\) , supported by NII \((+12\% y / y)\) and lower opex \((+3\% y / y)\) ; and 2) CB conversion into equities in 2Q led to improvements in the capital position. On the negative side: 1) we haven't observed signs of easing NIM pressure. 1H25 NIM contracted by 5bps h/h, the magnitude of which is larger vs. 2H24; 2) although overall asset quality metrics remain stable, we note rising AQ risks in the retail segment. Retail NPL % increased by 25bps h/h in 1H25. In addition, we expect short- term share price pressure from China Life's share reduction in BoHZ (announced on July 15). We maintain our Neutral rating.

- 2Q NII growth further improved, supported by deposit cost management. In 2Q25, BoHZ's NII growth of \(+12\%\) y/y \((+1\% q / q)\) further improved from \(7\%\) y/y in 1Q25 and \(6\%\) y/y in 4Q24. In the details, 2Q interest income was \(+1\%\) y/y while interest expense contracted by \(6\%\) y/y, suggesting that the recovery in NII growth was mainly driven by deposit cost management.

- 2Q PPOP beat expectations, partly aided by a declining cost-income ratio. 2Q25 PPOP \((+7\%\) y/y) beat JPME by \(13\%\) . We note that 2Q revenue was \(+6\%\) y/y, while OPEX only increased by \(3\%\) y/y, leading to a 74bps y/y decline in the cost-income ratio. On a semi-annual basis, the 1H25 cost-income-ratio dropped by 56bps y/y.

- Capital position enhanced in 2Q25. BoHZ's CET1/Tier-1/CAR were \(9.74\% /11.98\% /14.64\%\) in 2Q25, improving by \(73 / 64 / 59\) bps respectively from 1Q25 -levels. BoHZ has completed the convertible bond's conversion into equities in 2Q25 which improved its capital level. The shareholder meeting approved the 1H25 interim dividend plan in June 2025 while BoHZ has not announced payout details with its 1H25 report.

- Magnitude of NIM contraction (h/h) in 1H25 was larger vs 2H24. BoHZ's NIM contracted by 5bps h/h in 1H25, vs. -2bps h/h in 2H24 and -3bps h/h in 1H24. In the details, 1H25 asset yield declined by 31bps h/h, mainly dragged by a 38bps h/h decrease in loan yield. On the liability side, deposit cost reduced by 20bps h/h in 1H. Although NIM pressure persisted in 1H25, management expects the magnitude of FY25 NIM contraction to be lower than that of FY24 (NIM -9bps y/y in FY24).

- **Retail asset quality shows signs of risks:** AQ metrics delivered mixed messages. 2Q NPL ratio remained flat q/q at 0.76% and SML ratio improved by 3bps q/q. NPL coverage ratio dropped by 9pcts q/q in 2Q25, while the absolute level of 521% remained the highest among our covered CRBs. Corporate asset quality remained stable, with corporate NPL% declining by 10bps h/h in 1H25. However, we note AQ pressure from the retail segment. Retail NPL ratio surged by 25bps h/h, with personal business loans (NPL %+35bps h/h) seeing more AQ pressure.

- BoHZ has achieved high-quality growth with solid asset quality. Its ROE reached a low point in 2018 and we think it can remain on an uptrend due to the resilient local economy and low credit costs.- Media (digital economy and culture) and technology innovation industries feature prominently in Hangzhou's local economy. By choosing to focus on SME clients in these sectors, BoHZ could build up its own moat based on the familiarity and understanding of local clients.- BoHZ has strong relationships with local governments. We believe LGFV-related loans are more exposed to repricing risks, but we are comfortable with asset quality given solid health of the local economy in Zhejiang province.- We are Neutral on BoHZ because its shareholder returns are less attractive than peers. Its dividend payout ratio of 24% was lower than covered CRB peers' average of 27% in 2024, and our FY25E dividend yield of 4.0% (post CB conversion) is \(\sim 50\) bps lower than CRB peers.
Our Dec- 25 price target of Rmb15.50 is based on a dividend discount model, assuming a cost of equity of \(13.6\%\) , normalized ROE of \(11.3\%\) and a terminal date of 31 December 2027.
